		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Booster draft...what should you grab?<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.29)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=14360'>Joseph "Quickbeam" Conley</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=14360&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> May 19, 2003</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> So you&#39;re going to a booster draft tournament, and you have no idea what to do? Read on... <br />
The top cards you want are listed below. I&#39;ll add a explaintion. <br />
#1. Defend It and Hope. This is an awesome card. It ruthlessly slaughters any Dunland decks you face, because they don&#39;t have any copies of Hides. I always grab every Defend It I see. It&#39;s awesome against Uruk-hai, too. <br />
#2. Grima, Chief Counselor. Everyone there will be playing rainbow fellowships because that&#39;s what they got. The odds are against you getting this card, but if you do, you&#39;ve sealed up your victory. I pulled one at the Black Rider bounty and seriously screwed several people with it (namely Ryan French - sorry, man). <br />
#3. Merry, Learned Guide. I gathered up 5 copies of this guy at one draft, and just discarded and re-played him from my hand the entire game long. Pippin, Woolly-footed Rascal is good too, but be careful about your burdens. He might have Easterling corruption. <br />
#4. Smeagol, Old Noser. Since you may re-shuffle your draw deck during the game, if you discard a few key cards it doesn&#39;t matter, they&#39;ll come up again. This is great for double-moving, and combined with Aragorn, Wingfoot makes bouncing simple and fun. <br />
<br />
When you open your draft pack, immediately divide your cards in FP and Shadow piled. Take a quick count of the cards, and count your companions (A guy got only 7 FP cards and 2 companions in his pack once) You need to establish several things quickly. <br />
First, who is your main fighter? Who&#39;s the guy who&#39;s going to skirmish every turn? Who do you absolutely have to keep alive to the bitter end? Mark him, and set him aside. Start making notes in your head of which cards to look for, like Eomer&#39;s Spear, Ranger&#39;s Sword, or an unbound hobbit. Also mentally count your companions. I usually try to run about 10 companions. If you have Merry and Pippin you can use 11, play the Hobbits and then discard them, then take their places with better fighters.  <br />
THen look at your Shadow side. If it&#39;s Uruk Site control, you want Uruk-hai that bonus from controlled sites, and Attack on Helm&#39;s Deep. <br />
When you open your first pack, keep in mind that you shouldn&#39;t just grab the rare or foil. If it&#39;s an absolutely to die-for card, you can get it, but otherwise forget it, pick something you&#39;ll use. Commons are better than rares in booster drafts. <br />
When selected shadow cards, make absolutely sure that if the card you&#39;re getting isn&#39;t from the same culture as the rest of your minions, it most have NO CULTURAL ENFORCEMENT! I draft reletively cheap minions, maybe 1 expensive one, and absolutely no events for guys that I only have a few copies of. At the end of the pack you&#39;ll almost always get the &#39;throwaway card&#39; which nobody wants and you can&#39;t use. Just set it aside, it doesn&#39;t matter. <br />
After the first pack, put your Free Peoples and Shadow together and count them again. YOu want to have a almost equal amount of cards each time, because if you don&#39;t have 30 of each side you forfiet the tournament, or at least you must fill up the gaps with useless cards. Mark off which holes you&#39;ve filled, how many companions you have, and what to try to get in the next pack. <br />
I don&#39;t draft sites. I always get at least 1 in the throwaway card, but I don&#39;t want to. When I put together my site path I always start with the Riddermark, most draft packs have Aragorn and you&#39;ll probably draw one. If you don&#39;t get Aragorn, and you do draw a Legolas and you see an Eastemnet Gullies (or whatever it&#39;s title) go ahead and grab it up, but otherwise don&#39;t bother. Also, use Palantir Chamber for site 9. People bid a lot and don&#39;t mind adding burdens, you can often get a site 9 swarm, even with stuff like Raiders and Uruk-hai.  <br />
When you are finished drafting, double-check you cards to make sure the sides add up, and stow the extras away safely, but separate from your other cards. (you can switch out cards between rounds) It&#39;s better, when assembling your deck, to cut a card you think you might need than add a card you know is useless. Since you can re-shuffle you might get this worthless card in your hand at site 9 when you desperately need a minion. <br />
YOur finished deck size should be about 31 cards for each side. Since you don&#39;t have hardly an skirmish events when you re-shuffle your draw deck will be almost entirely minions, so you can swarm him at 9. Make sure you play fast, you want a discard pile with several minions in it for Palantir chamber, and a handful of them. I win most of my games by killing the other guy at 9. (that&#39;s how I won all 4 of the Black Rider Bounty games)  <br />
I suggest casing your cards up before you start to play, otherwise a rare or foil in your deck might get beat up. (In my book, that is the ultimate sin of all) <br />
So happy drafting, and may you kick all your opponent&#39;s butts. And if you slaughter them totally because of this article and win the tourney, remember my take is 50%.  <br></font><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php?id=4744&view=1&PHPSESSID=...328fedb22570524062aeb1303'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php?PHPSESSID=...328fedb22570524062aeb1303'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/lotr/main/join.php?PHPSESSID=...328fedb22570524062aeb1303'> become a registered member</a></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
